NDNS_NTimes_18_64: The number of times this food was consumed (after cutting on ages of people 18-64)
NDNS_MeanQuantity_18_64: The average quantity consumed per instance (after cutting on ages of people 18-64)
NDNS_StdQuantity_18_64: The standard deviation of the quantity consumed per instance  (after cutting on ages of people 18-64)
Units: Units - a tidied up version of the Units given in NDNS (e.g. 'grams' -> 'Grams')

Description: This is copied from the NDNS nutrient databank
Dilution: This is copied from the NDNS nutrient databank
Comment: The comment field from the NDNS nutrient databank

CO2eRefSLBBook: \gNote{GHGE:Beans, canned}Taking an average of UK (1.7\coeratio{} after subtracting the can) and imported (1.8\coeratio{}) beans, values from~\citet{Frankowska:2019veg} for beans in a can. CO2eRefSLBBook: I have taken the values from \citep{Amienyo:2012bg}, see in particular their Figure 5, which shows the contributions from the separate processes. I have subtracted off their number for the packaging (174 g CO2e / litre) and grouped all the other contributions together (388-174 g CO2e / litre), for the 0.5 litre PET bottle. Regarding the bubbles in the drink, the amount of carbon dioxide fizz is 0.6\% the weight of the drink (\citealt{Amienyo:2012bg} Table 1), so a 0.5 litre bottle contains 3 grams of carbon dioxide, which is less than 2 \% of the total emissions caused by the drink and its packaging (388 g CO2e / litre * 0.5 litres = 194 g CO2e). }

CO2eRefSLBBook: The value from CCalc2 [todo citep CCalc2] for recycled tinplate (steel) is 1.68 kg CO2e / kg (62\% recycled) and 2.7 kg CO2e / kg for virgin (not recycled) tinplate. % [old text follows: I recommend the fantastic book by Julian Allwood and David Cullen to learn all about the carbon footprints of materials, including steel. See also Tesco (2012). "Product carbon footprint summary."  \citeyearpar{url:1066:Tesco_carbon_footprints} \url{http://www.tescoplc.com/assets/files/cms/Tesco_Product_Carbon_Footprints_Summary\%281\%29.pdf}  AW 2019/09/04 Retrieved 15/02/2015 We can use a fit to 220g, 420g, 850g tins to estimate fraction due to beans and fraction due to tin Assume that the gCO2e for a tin = $a \times$ weight of beans $+ c \times$ the surface area of tin $\sim a r^3 + b r^2$ (assuming a spherical tin). Therefore the CO2e per 100g of beans = $a + c \times$ (the weight of beans)$^(-1/3)$ Use the maximum and minimum weights from the Tesco table to fit the values for $a$ and $c$ gives $c = (110-150) / (0.106 - 0.17) = 625$ and $a = 150 - c * 0.17 = 150 - 625 * 0.17 = 44$. So this means the beans contribute 44 gCO2e per 100g beans and the can contributes the rest e.g. for the 420g can of beans it contributes 86g CO2e /100g of beans, or 360g CO2e for the whole can. i.e. 2/3 of the CO2e %}]
